PRE-MARKET AUSTRALIAN, JAPANESE AND SOUTH KOREAN STOCK NEWS: Vocus Communications (VOC AT) receives proposal from EQT Infrastructure to acquire the Co. for AUD 5.25/Shr
content:
AUSTRALIA

Flight Centre (FLT AT) - Corporate Travel Management is said to have approached Co. about a potential merger. (AFR)

GPT Group (GOT AT) - Co. acquires logistics assets in Sydney for AUD 212mln. (Newswires)

Suncorp-Metway (SUN AT) - Co. CEO and MD resigns, while its CFO Johnston is appointed acting CEO. (Newswires)

TPG Telecom (TPG AT) - Federal proceedings have commenced seeking order that merger with Vodafone Hutchinson will not have the effect of lessening competition. (Newswires)

Vocus Communications (VOC AT) - Co. board is looking at beginning formal sale process after it received some expressions of interest in which EQT Infrastructure proposed to acquire the Co. for AUD 5.25/Shr. (AFR)

Woolworths (WOW AT) - Co. completes AUD 1.7bln off market buyback. (Newswires)

 

JAPAN

Nissan (7201 JT) - Fiat Chrysler (F IM) is said to be in talks with Renault (RNO FP) about forming an extensive alliance which could result in them joining large portions of their businesses. (Newswires)

Toyota (7203 JT) - Co. is to build its first assembly plant in Myanmar. (Nikkei)

Trade - US President Trump said US and Japan are nearing a big trade announcement but also noted that they can wait until after the Japanese elections for a trade deal with Japan, which indicates an agreement may not happen during his visit this week. (Nikkei)

Other News - Japanese Economic Minister Motegi said the plan to increase the sales tax is unchanged and economic growth is intact, although there were separate comments from Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary Kato said the outcome of US-China trade talks is key to tax hike decision. (Newswires)

 

SOUTH KOREA

Lotte Corp (004990 KS) - Co. will sell 80% stake in Lotte Card to MBK Partners for KRW 1.38tln and will sell 53.5% stake in Lotte Insurance to JKL Partners for KRW 373.4bln. (Newswires)

Samsung Biologics (207940 KS) - Court rejected arrest warrant for Co. CEO who is suspicion of abetting destruction of evidence concerning accounting scandal. (Yonhap)

Samsung Electronics (005930 KS) - 2 senior executives were arrested in accounting probe. (Newswires)

Automakers - South Korea government is mulling extending tax cuts for autos. (Newswires)

Other News US President Trump suggested he has confidence North Korean Chairman Kim will keep his promise despite some people being disturbed by North Korea recent firing off small weapons. (Twitter)

US National Security Adviser Bolton said the US had recently had little communication with North Korea. (Newswires)

subject: DAILY ASIA-PAC OPENING NEWS
content:
ASIA-PAC

China Global Times Editor thinks a US-China trade deal will be reached but currently there are factors complicating a resolution, while the Editor also suggested US confidence in believing it can quickly press China to submit is the biggest obstacle to reaching a deal and the trade war may last for a long time. (Twitter)

Chinese envoy said there are no official talks of a meeting between US President Trump and Chinese President Xi. In related news, China State Planner VP said China's economy can remain healthy, steady and with sustainable growth despite impact from the China-US trade war. (Newswires)

US President Trump’s administration is taking steps towards issuing even more restrictions on exports of high-tech goods to China in which the Commerce Department will soon recommend rolling back regulations that made it easier for US companies to export certain goods that have both civilian and military purposes according to sources. (Politico Morning Money)

US President Trump said US and Japan are nearing a big trade announcement but also noted that they can wait until after the Japanese elections for a trade deal with Japan, which indicates an agreement may not happen during his visit this week. (Nikkei) 

 

UK/EU

UK PM May announced she will step down on June 7th, while a leadership contest will begin in the following week and she will continue to serve as PM until a new leader is selected. (Newswires)

UK Foreign Minister Hunt said he will stand for Tory party leadership following PM May's resignation and 1922 Executive Chair Brady stood down as 1922 Chair as he confirmed he is considering running for PM. Furthermore, former cabinet ministers Gove, Raab and Leadsom have also joined the leadership race, while front-runner Johnson said the UK will leave the EU on 31st October with a deal or no deal and that he will go back to the EU to discuss the Northern Irish backstop. (Newswires)

Irish Foreign Minister Coveney now believes a No-Deal Brexit is more likely than ever, but still thinks it can be avoided. (Newswires)

UK Retail Sales (Apr) M/M 0.0% vs. Exp. -0.3% (Prev. 1.1%, Rev. 1.2%). (Newswires) UK Retail Sales (Apr) Y/Y 5.2% vs. Exp. 4.6% (Prev. 6.7%)

Early exit polls indicate the center-right and center-left groups are set remain the biggest groups but have fallen short of the majority needed in the 751-strong assembly for the 1st time since the 1970 with the European People’s Party projected to win 177 seats (Prev. 217 seats) and Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats projected to win 147 seats (Prev. 189). Meanwhile, Liberals, euroskeptic and Green parties are projected to gain ground which reportedly could complicate coalition talks. (Newswires/WSJ)

Greek Prime Minister Tsipras said he cannot ignore election results and has called for snap elections following a heavy defeat by his Syriza party at European Parliament elections which trails behind opposition New Democracy by around 9 points. (Newswires)

Fitch affirmed Portugal at BBB; Outlook revised to Positive. (Newswires) 

 

COMMODITIES

Baker Hughes (May 24) US oil rigs -5 at 797, US nat gas rigs +1 at 186, total US rigs -4 at 983. (Newswires)

 

GEOPOLITICS

US President Trump approved sending 1,500 troops to the Middle East which he stated was for "mostly protective" reasons. In related news, US military said that intelligence suggests a "campaign" by Iran that ties together threats across the region, while it also alleged Iranian Revolutionary Guards are directly responsible for attacks on tankers outside the UAE. (Newswires) 

 

GLOBAL NEWS

French authorities are treating a parcel bomb explosion that injured 13 pedestrians in central Lyon on Friday as a terror attack. (FT)

Magnitude 8 earthquake reportedly hit Northern Peru. (Newswires) 

 

US

US President Trump reiterated his view that US growth would have exceeded 3% if the Fed did not raise rates last year. (Newswires)

US Durable Goods (Apr) -2.1% vs. Exp. -2.0% (Prev. 2.6%, Rev. 1.7%). (Newswires)

 

MARKET RECAP

Boeing (BA) opened higher on Friday, buoyed by constructive comments from regulators on the 737 MAX jet software fix, however, shares came off slightly on reports the SEC was probing its disclosures on the 737 later in the session. Merger talk between Total System Services (TSS) and Global Payments (GPN) saw both stocks surge. Apple (AAPL) and Amazon (AMZN) lifted markets on the open on a positive mention at Wedbush and Piper Jaffray respectively. Constellation Brands (STZ) suffered from a downgrade at Morgan Stanley. Autodesk (ADSK) and Foot Locker (FL) both nosedived after missing top- and bottom-line estimates. Conversely, Hewlett Packard Enterprise (HPE) and HP (HPQ) traded higher on the back of their earnings reports. Snap (SNAP) caught a bid on the open following reports that it would launch a feature allowing posts to include music. Vale (VALE) made gains on a tailwind from upgrades at both BAML and RBC Capital. Centene (CNC) spiked higher in later trade on reports activist investor Third Point had taken a stake in it and is pushing for it to sell itself before it acquires WellCare (WCG). S&P 500 +0.2% at 2827, Dow Jones +0.4% at 25594, NASDAQ-100 -0.1% at 7301.

Treasury trade was lacklustre and sideways ahead of the long weekend; the bias was for higher yields with the US Treasury curve bear-flattening. In early trade, the dip was attributed to profit taking, and in European trade, the complex took its cue from the Gilt, after UK PM May announced a timeline for her departure. After Europeans left, sideways trade resumed, with Thursday's ranges largely remaining in tact. Major curve spreads tightened at settlement. US T-Note futures (M9) settled 10 ticks lower at 124-28+.
